<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-10-05T16:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-10-05T16:36:00-05:00" n="884" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d884">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">818.6363Am6/53: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at San José</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Chase</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">San
                                            José</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-10-05T16:00:00-05:36"><hi rend="italic">October
                                            5, 1920—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received October 6—10:55
                                    a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>69. Today the Costa Rican Government published the reply to the
                                British Government relative to Amory concession and the Royal Bank
                                of Canada denying their right to diplomatic intervention and
                                advising that the Costa Rican courts are available to them.
                                Particulars by mail.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Chase</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>